HOUSE RESOLUTION 207
By Rudder
A RESOLUTION to honor the Franklin County Garden Club during
National Garden Week.
WHEREAS, gardeners have a passion for nurturing the beauty and resources of the
earth through the planting of seeds, the care of all plants, and the riches of their efforts; they
seek to add beauty, splendor, fragrance, and nutrition to our lives through the growing of herbs,
vegetables, foliage, and flowers; and
WHEREAS, gardeners work to preserve our State's traditional spirit of independence
and initiative through innovation and hard work; they advocate for the importance of all
creatures, large and small, that share our world, and their roles in a balanced and productive
ecology; and
WHEREAS, gardening furnishes a challenging and productive activity for citizens—those
just learning as well as those who have years of experience; it also promotes a healthy lifestyle
that lasts a lifetime, helps reduce stress from other areas of life, and teaches that rewards can
come from diligent efforts; and
WHEREAS, garden clubs across the State and nation make a difference in the
communities wherein they reside and work; one such garden club is the Franklin County
Garden Club, whose members have taken strides to preserve the environment, enhance the
beauty of their community, and educate the next generation on the benefits of gardening; and
WHEREAS, established by Elizabeth Drake of EB Drake Nursery in 1929, the club
passionately beautifies the community and promotes gardening to others, including teachers
and students at Clark Memorial Elementary School, where they undertook a successful project
to restore the historic Carrick Academy Bell; and
HR0207
018125
- 1 -

WHEREAS, the Carrick Academy Bell project, the largest ever undertaken by the club,
was in partnership with Clark Memorial Elementary School, the Rotary Club, a local paint
company, and a restoration company; the Franklin County Garden Club worked with partners to
trim bushes, replace landscape fabric, provide a new flag, repair the light for the school sign,
and plant a flower bed; and
WHEREAS, this project, which won the National Garden Club Plant America contest, is
a testament to the dedication and resourcefulness of the Franklin County Garden Club and a
shining example of the important role that gardeners and garden clubs can play in their
communities; and
WHEREAS, it is our privilege to honor this outstanding organization and its members
during National Garden Week; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we honor and
commend the Franklin County Garden Club during National Garden Week, June 7-13, 2026,
extending our sincere appreciation for the many worthy efforts of garden club members in
Franklin County and throughout this State.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
